<section xml:id="sec_seventh-heateq" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
  <title>Heat Equation</title>
  <introduction>
   <figure xml:id="fig-fig78">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="fig78.png" width ="45%"/>
</figure>
   <p>
    we know that heat flows from hotter region to colder region inside a solid by 
    conduction. Physical experiments reveal that the rate of flow is proportional 
    to the temperature gradient, which implies that the velocity <m>v</m> of the heat 
    flow in a body is given by 	<m>\vec{v}=-k  \,grad \,u =-k \vec{\nabla} u</m>. 
    Where k is a constant, known as thermal conductivity of the body; 
    <m>u(x,y,z,t)</m> is the temperature at a point P and <m>t</m> is the time. 
    Now, consider a volume <m>V</m> of the body enclosed by the boundary surface <m>S</m>, 
    as shown in figure <xref ref="fig-fig78"/>. Then the amount of heat leaving the body per unit time 
    is given by 
    <men xml:id="eqn-heat_eqn1">
      -\frac{\partial Q}{\partial t}=\iint\limits_{s}\vec{v}\cdot \hat{n}\,ds
    </men>
    
  
    But from Gauss's Divergence Theorem,  we have 
    <me>
      \iint\limits_{s}\vec{v}\cdot \hat{n}\,ds =\iiint\limits_{V}div\,\vec{v}\,dV
    </me>

where <m>V</m> is the volume enclosed by surface S. 
<me>
  =  \iiint\limits_{V}\vec{\nabla}\cdot\vec{v}\,dV =\iiint\limits_{V}\vec{\nabla}\cdot\left(-k \vec{\nabla} u\right)\,dV 
</me>
<men xml:id="eqn-heat_eqn2">
   =-k\iiint\limits_{V}\vec{\nabla}\cdot\vec{\nabla} u\,dV = -k\iiint\limits_{V}\nabla^{2}u\,dV 
</men>
    </p>
   <p>
    Now if <m> \rho</m> be the density of the body, <m>c</m> be the specific heat 
    capacity, then the total heat <m>Q</m> contained in the body is given by 
    <men xml:id="eqn-heat_eqn3">
      	Q=\iiint\limits_{V}c\rho u\,dV  
    </men>
    <m>[\because\quad Q = mc\theta =V\rho c \theta ] </m> here <m>\theta</m> = temperature, <m>u</m>]

so the rate of decrease of <m>Q</m> is given by
<men xml:id="eqn-heat_eqn4">
  -\frac{\partial Q}{\partial t}=-\iiint\limits_{V}c\rho \frac{\partial u}{\partial t}\,dV
</men>

This must be equal to the amount of heat leaving the body in unit time, i.e., 
<me>
  -\iiint\limits_{V}c\rho \frac{\partial u}{\partial t}\,dV = -k \iiint\limits_{V}\nabla^{2}u\,dV
</me>
or,
<men xml:id="eqn-heat_eqn5">
  \iiint\limits_{V}\left[c\rho \frac{\partial u}{\partial t}-k\nabla^{2}u\right]\,dV=0
</men>
 	
Since the surface <m>S</m> is arbitrary, the volume enclosed by surface <m>\,dS</m> is 
<m>\,dV\neq 0</m>.Thus the integrands must be zero. i.e., 
<me>
  c\rho \frac{\partial u}{\partial t}= k\nabla^{2}u
</me>

	or, 	
  <me>
    \frac{\partial u}{\partial t}=\frac{k}{c\rho} \nabla^{2}u
  </me>
<men xml:id="eqn-heat_eqn6">
  \therefore \quad \frac{\partial u}{\partial t} =h^{2}\nabla^{2}u
</men>
	
This equation is known as heat equation. The quantity <m>h^{2}</m> is known 
as diffusivity of the solid, and is defined as the ratio of thermal conductivity 
and heat capacity of solid per unit volume.
    </p>
    <p><term>note:</term>   </p>
      <ol marker="i.">
        <li>
          <p>
            If there is no heat flow in <m>z</m>- direction (or temperature of the body 
            is independent of <m>z</m>), then 
            <me>
              \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial z^{2}}=0
            </me>
            and heat equation 
            <men xml:id="eqn-heat_eqn7">
             \frac{1}{h^{2}} \frac{\partial u}{\partial t}= \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial y^{2}} 
            </men>
            is known as heat equation for two - dimensional flow parallel to <m>xy</m> plane.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            If the flow of heat is only along <m>x</m>- axis, the heat equation reduces 
            to 
            <men xml:id="eqn-heat_eqn8">
              \frac{1}{h^{2}} \frac{\partial u}{\partial t}= \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}} 
            </men>
           and is known as the heat equation for one - dimensional flow.
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            When the temperature does not change with time (or <m>u</m> is independent 
            of time) then 
            <me>
              \frac{\partial u}{\partial t} =0
            </me>
            and equation <xref ref="eqn-heat_eqn6"/> reduces to 	
            <men xml:id="eqn-heat_eqn9">
              \nabla^{2}u=0
            </men>
            and is known as heat equation for steady - state <idx><h>steady-state 
            equation </h></idx> flow, which is a famous Laplace's Equation.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol> 
     </introduction>
 
 <subsection xml:id="subsec-1D_heat">
  <title>One Dimensional Equation of Heat Flow</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      The one-dimensional heat equation describes the flow of heat in a medium along 
      a single spatial dimension. It is a partial differential equation that relates 
      the rate of change of temperature with respect to time to the second derivative 
      of temperature with respect to the spatial coordinate.

The general form of the one-dimensional heat equation is given in <xref ref="eqn-heat_eqn8"/>.
where <m>u(x, t)</m> represents the temperature at position x and time t, <m>h^2</m> is the 
thermal diffusivity (a material-specific constant), and <m>\frac{\partial}{\partial t} </m> 
and <m>\frac{\partial^2}{\partial x^2}</m> denote the partial derivatives with 
respect to time and space, respectively. This equation describes how the temperature 
at a given point changes over time due to the heat flow and diffusion within the medium. 
The second derivative term on the right-hand side accounts for the spatial variations in 
temperature, while the left-hand side represents the rate of change of temperature with 
respect to time. 
    </p>
    <p>
      Solving the one-dimensional heat equation involves finding the temperature 
      distribution <m>u(x, t)</m>  as a function of both position and time, 
      given the initial condition <m>u(x, 0)</m>  and appropriate boundary conditions 
      that specify the temperature at the boundaries of the medium. The solution to 
      the one-dimensional heat equation can be obtained using various analytical 
      or numerical methods, such as separation of variables, finite difference methods, 
      or Fourier series expansion, depending on the specific problem and boundary conditions.
      </p>
  </introduction>

  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-1Dheat_0ed">
    <title>If ends of a bar are at temperature zero</title>
    <p>
      Consider a bar of uniform cross section of length <m>\lambda</m> whose both 
      ends are maintained at temperature zero, and the initial temperature to be 
      given as <m>f(x)</m> as shown in figure <xref ref="fig-fig79"/>. If one end of the bar is fixed at the origin and distances 
      along the bar are denoted by <m>x</m>, then we have 
      <men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_0ed1">
        \frac{\partial u}{\partial t} =h^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}	
      </men>
      </p>
      <figure xml:id="fig-fig79">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="fig79.png" width ="45%"/>
</figure>
      <p>
        The boundary conditions are <m>u(0,t)=0=u(\lambda,t) </m>	for 
        <m>t\geq 0 </m>  and the initial condition <m>u(x,0) =f(x)</m> for 
        <m>0 \lt x \lt \lambda</m>. Let us assume that 	
        <men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_0ed2">
          u(x,t) = X(x)T(t)
        </men>
 
be the solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_0ed1"/>.
Hence equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_0ed1"/> becomes -
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_0ed3">
  \frac{1}{X}\frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}} =\frac{1}{h^{2}T}\frac{\partial T}{\partial t} =-\lambda^{2}  \quad \text{(say)}
</men>
or,
<me>
  \frac{1}{h^{2}T}\frac{\partial T}{\partial t}= -\lambda^{2} \Rightarrow T =Ce^{-\lambda^{2}h^{2}t} 
</me>
and 
<me>
  \frac{1}{X}\frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}} = -\lambda^{2} \Rightarrow X=A\cos\lambda x+B\sin\lambda x 
</me>

Therefore, solution <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_0ed2"/> becomes
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_0ed4">
  u(x,t) = (A\cos\lambda x+B\sin\lambda x)Ce^{-\lambda^{2}h^{2}t}
</men>
        </p>
        <p>
          But, 
          <me>
            u(0,t)=0=A\cdot Ce^{-\lambda^{2}h^{2}t} \Rightarrow A=0 \quad \because C \neq 0 
          </me>
      again, 
      <me>
        u(\lambda,t) =0= B\sin\lambda \lambda)Ce^{-\lambda^{2}h^{2}t}
      </me>
			
As <m>B</m> should not be zero, <m>\sin\lambda \lambda =0 =\sin n\pi</m>. Or,
<me>
  \lambda = \frac{n\pi}{\lambda}, \quad  n=1,2,3,\cdots 
</me>

putting <m>A</m> and <m>\lambda </m> in equation,<xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_0ed4"/>, we get- 
<me>
  u(x,t)=B\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda} Ce^{-n^{2}\pi^{2}h^{2}t/\lambda^{2}} = A_{n}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}e^{-n^{2}\pi^{2}h^{2}t/\lambda^{2}}
</me>
put <m>[BC=A_{n}].</m>
          </p>
          <p>
            summing over for all values of <m>n</m>, this eqn. becomes 
            <men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_0ed5">
              u(x,t) = \sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty} A_{n}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}e^{-n^{2}\pi^{2}h^{2}t/\lambda^{2}} 
            </men>
            	
also, <m>u(x,0) =f(x),</m>  we have 
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_0ed6">
  	f(x) = \sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty} A_{n}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}
</men>

which is Fourier sine series with 
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_0ed7">
  A_{n} = \frac{2}{\lambda}\int\limits_{0}^{\lambda}f(x)\sin\frac{n\pi x}{l}\,dx	 
</men>
            </p>
  </subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-1Dheat_inslbar">
  <title>If ends of the bar are insulated</title>
  <p>
   The boundary conditions of the problem are 
   <m>\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}=0	</m> at <m>x=0</m>  and <m>\lambda</m>	[for <m>t\geq 0 </m>].
and <m>u=f(x)</m>	at <m>t=0</m>	[for <m>0 \lt x \lt \lambda</m>].
Then solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_0ed1"/> becomes
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_inslbar2">
  u=(A\cos\lambda x+B\sin\lambda x)Ce^{-\lambda^{2}h^{2}t}
</men>
or,
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_inslbar3">
  \frac{\partial u}{\partial x}=\left(-A\lambda\sin\lambda x+ B\lambda\cos\lambda x\right)Ce^{-\lambda^{2}h^{2}t}	
</men>

Putting <m>\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}=0</m> at <m>x=0</m> in equation 
<xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_inslbar3"/>, we get -
<me>
   0=B\lambda Ce^{-\lambda^{2}h^{2}t}
</me>

		or, <m>B=0 </m>, since, <m>C\neq 0{,} \lambda \neq 0</m>. 
Therefore, equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_inslbar2"/> becomes 
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_inslbar4">
  u=A\cos\lambda x\cdot Ce^{-\lambda^{2}h^{2}t}
</men>
or,
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_inslbar5">
  \frac{\partial u}{\partial x}=-A\lambda\sin\lambda x\cdot Ce^{-\lambda^{2}h^{2}t} 
</men>
    </p>
    <p>
      Putting <m>\frac{\partial u}{\partial x}=0</m> at <m>x=\lambda </m>  
      in equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_inslbar5"/>, we get - 
      <me>
        0=-AC\lambda\sin\lambda\lambda e^{-\lambda^{2}h^{2}t}
      </me>
      or,
      <me>
      \sin\lambda\lambda =0 =\sin n\pi \quad	[\text{since,}\quad  A, C \neq 0 ]  
      </me>
      or,
      <me>
        \lambda = \frac{n\pi}{\lambda}, 
      </me>
      where <m> n=1,2,3,\cdots</m>.
 
Hence the general solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_0ed1"/> becomes - 
<me>
  u=AC\cos\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}e^{-n^{2}\pi^{2}h^{2}t/\lambda^{2}} =B_{n}e^{-n^{2}\pi^{2}h^{2}t/\lambda^{2}} \cos\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}   
</me>
		put <m>AC= B_{n} </m>.] 
		
However, for the given boundary conditions the above solution satisfies all the 
values of <m>n</m> including zero.  Hence the solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_0ed1"/> 
is given by 
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_inslbar6">
  u=B_{o}+\sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty}B_{n}e^{-n^{2}\pi^{2}h^{2}t/\lambda^{2}} \cos\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}
</men>
Now,
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_inslbar7">
  f(x) = u(x,0) = B_{o}+\sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty} B_{n} \cos\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}
</men>


from which we can find, 	
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_inslbar8">
  	B_{n}=\frac{2}{\lambda}\int\limits_{0}^{\lambda}f(x)\cos\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}\,dx
</men>
and 
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_inslbar9">
   B_{o}=\frac{1}{\lambda}\int\limits_{0}^{\lambda}f(x)\,dx
</men>
      </p>
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-1Dheat_u0">
  <title>If one end of a bar at temperature <m>u_{o}</m> and the other at temperature zero</title>
  <p>
    Suppose the bar is given the constant temperature <m>f(x)</m> initially and face 
    <m>x=0</m> is kept at temperature zero, while the face <m>x=\lambda</m> is kept at 
    constatn temperature <m>u_{o}</m> for <m>t \gt 0</m>, then the boundary conditions 
    of the problem becomes
    <men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u01">
      \left.\begin{aligned}	
		u(0,t) = 0\\
		u(\lambda,t) = u_{o}
	\end{aligned}\right\} \text{for all}\quad t
    </men>
    and 
  <men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u02">
    	u(x,0)=f(x)  \quad (say)
  </men>
  
			   
The equation of heat flow is given by 
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u03">
  \frac{\partial u}{\partial t} =h^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}		
</men>

Let the solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_u03"/> be
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u04">
  u(x,t) = X(x)T(t)
</men>
or,
<me>
  \frac{\partial u}{\partial t} =X\frac{\partial T}{\partial t} 		
</me>
and 
<me>
  \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}=T\frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}} 
</me>
	
Substituting these in equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_u03"/>, we get -
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u05">
  \frac{1}{X}\frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}} =\frac{1}{h^{2}T}\frac{\partial T}{\partial t} =-\alpha^{2}  \quad  (say)
</men>
Hence,
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u06">
 \frac{\partial T}{\partial t} =-\alpha^{2}h^{2}T  \quad \Rightarrow T =Ae^{-\alpha^{2}h^{2}t} 
</men>
and 
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u07">
  \frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}}  = -\alpha^{2}X
</men>
or,
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u08">
  \frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}} + \alpha^{2}X = 0 \quad \Rightarrow X=B\cos\alpha x+C\sin\alpha x
</men>
Hence, 
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u09">
  u(x,t)=(a\cos\alpha x+b\sin\alpha x)e^{-\alpha^{2}h^{2}t}
</men>

This solution shows <m>u(x,t) \to 0 </m> at <m>t \to \infty</m> for all <m>x</m> 
but the boundary condition shows that <m>u(x,t) = u_{o} </m> at <m>x=\lambda</m>, 
a non - zero constant. Therefore, the solution <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_u09"/> 
though satisfies the boundary condition at <m>x=0</m> does not satisfy it at <m>x=\lambda</m>. 
Hence we should add one more solution to this solution so that <m>u(x,t) \to u_{o} </m> at 
<m>x=\lambda</m> when <m>t \to \infty</m> and at the same time it becomes zero at 
<m>x=0</m>. Such solution may be obtained by choosing the constant <m>\alpha^{2}</m>  
equal to zero. Then equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_u07"/> becomes <m>T=A</m> 
and equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_u08"/> reduces to 	
<me>
  \frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}}=0 \Rightarrow X=Bx+C.
</me>

Hence, solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_u03"/> in this case is given by

<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u010">
  	u(x,t) =A(Bx+C)=a' x+b'
</men>

	    		
The complete solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_u03"/> is thus -
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u011">
  u(x,t)=(a' x+b')+(a\cos\alpha x+b\sin\alpha x)e^{-\alpha^{2}h^{2}t}
</men>
or,
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u012">
  u(x,t)=u_{s}(x)+u_{T}(x,t)
</men>


where <m>u_{s}(x)</m> is the temperature distribution after a long interval of time 
when there exists steady state of temperature and <m>u_{T}(x,t)</m> is the transient 
temperature which tends to zero as  <m>t</m> increases. Now, for <m>t \to \infty</m>,  
<m>u(0,t)= 0</m>, and <m>u(\lambda,t)=u_{o}</m> and from equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_u011"/>, 
we have -
<me>
  0=b'+0 \quad  \therefore  b' =0 
</me>
and 
<me>
  u_{o}=a' \lambda
</me>

<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u013">
  \therefore a'=u_{o}/\lambda
</men>
     

so that	<m>u_{s}(x)=(u_{o}/\lambda)x </m>. Thus solution <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_u011"/> (7.2.1.12) 
reduces to 
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u014">
  u(x,t)=\frac{u_{o}x}{\lambda}+(a\cos\alpha x+b\sin\alpha x)e^{-\alpha^{2}h^{2}t}
</men>

which must be zero at <m>x=0</m> for every value of <m>t</m>. Thus we have <m>a=0</m>.
and 		
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u015">
  u(x,t)=\frac{u_{o}x}{\lambda}+b\sin\alpha x \,e^{-\alpha^{2}h^{2}t}
</men>

which must give <m>u(\lambda,t)=u_{o}</m> for every <m>t</m>  and hence 
<m>\sin\alpha\lambda =0=\sin n\pi</m>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Or, <m>\alpha =\frac{n\pi}{\lambda}</m>,	where <m>n=1,2,3,\cdots</m>.
      Or,
      <men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u016">
        u(x,t) = \frac{u_{o}x}{\lambda}+\sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty} b_{n}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda} \,e^{-n^{2}\pi^{2}h^{2}t/\lambda}
      </men>
      
Constant <m>b_{n}</m> may be calculated by using the initial condition <m>u(x,0)=f(x)</m>.
Hence,
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u017">
  f(x)-\frac{u_{o}x}{\lambda}=\sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty} b_{n}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}
</men>
and 
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_u018">
  b_{n}=\frac{2}{\lambda}\int\limits_{0}^{\lambda}\left[f(x)-\frac{u_{o}x}{\lambda}\right]\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}\,dx
</men>
      </p>
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-1Dheat_infbar">
  <title>Temperature in an infinite bar</title>
  <p>
    Let us consider an infinite bar of insulated surfaces. The initial temperature 
    on the bar is given as 
    <men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_infbar1">
      u(x,0)=f(x), \quad \text{for}  \quad -\infty \lt x \lt \infty
    </men>

The solution of one dimensional heat equaiton is given as
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_infbar2">
  	u(x,t) =X(x)T(t)=(a\cos\alpha x+b\sin \alpha x)e^{-\alpha^{2}h^{2}t}
</men>

This solution is periodic in <m>x</m> at <m>t=0</m>. But <m>f(x)</m> is not taken 
as periodic function, we shall therefore, use Fourier integral instead of Fourier 
series for the determination of constants  <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>. Let us assume 
the  arbitrary coefficients <m>a</m> and <m>b</m> to be the functions of  
<m>\alpha</m> i.e., <m>a=a(\alpha)</m>  and  <m>b=b(\alpha)</m>. Then 
<me>
  u(x,t)=\int\limits_{0}^{\infty}u(x,t,\alpha)\,d\alpha 
</me>

<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_infbar3">
  =\int\limits_{0}^{\infty}\{a(\alpha)\cos\alpha x+b(\alpha)\sin\alpha x\}e^{-\alpha^{2}h^{2}t}\,d\alpha
</men>
using initial condition, we have -
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_infbar4">
  u(x,0) =\int\limits_{0}^{\infty}\{a(\alpha)\cos\alpha x+b(\alpha)\sin\alpha x\}\,d\alpha =f(x)
</men>
  
from this equation, we get -
<me>
  a(\alpha) = \frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)\cos\alpha x\,dx=\frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(\mu)\cos\alpha \mu\,d\mu
</me>
and 
<me>
  b(\alpha) = \frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(x)\sin\alpha x\,dx=\frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(\mu)\sin\alpha \mu\,d\mu 
</me>
so that 
<me>
  u(x,0) = \frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{0}^{\infty}\left[\int\limits_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(\mu)\cos\alpha (x-\mu)\,d\mu\right]\,d\alpha
</me>

as such the equation <xref ref="eqn-1Dheat_infbar3"/> takes the form,
<me>
  	u(x,t) = \frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{0}^{\infty}\left[\int\limits_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(\mu)\cos\alpha (x-\mu)e^{-\alpha^{2}h^{2}t}\,d\mu\right]\,d\alpha
</me>
<men xml:id="eqn-1Dheat_infbar5">
  	=\frac{1}{\pi}\int\limits_{-\infty}^{\infty}f(\mu)\left[\cos\alpha(x-\mu)e^{-\alpha^{2}h^{2}t}\,d\alpha\right]\,d\mu
</men>

which gives the required temperature at any point at any time.
    </p>
</subsubsection>
 </subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-2D_heat">
  <title>Two Dimensional Equation of Heat Flow</title>
  <figure xml:id="fig-fig710">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="fig710.png" width ="45%"/>
</figure>
  <p>
    Consider the flow of heat in a metal plate of uniform thickness in the directions 
    parallel to the breadth of the plate. The surface of the plate is insulated as shown in 
    figure <xref ref="fig-fig710"/>. 
    Let <m>u(x,y,t)</m> be the temperature at any point <m>(x,y)</m> of the plate at 
    any time <m>t</m> is given by 

<men xml:id="eqn-2Dheat_sol1">
  \frac{\partial u}{\partial t}= h^{2} \left( \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial y^{2}}\right)	
</men>

If the edges are kept at zero temperature then the boundary conditions are 
<me>
   u(0,y,t) = u(a,y,t) =u(x,0,t) = u(x,b,t)= 0
</me>

and the initial condition is given as <m> u(x,y,0) = f(x,y)</m>.
	
	Let us assume that
  <men xml:id="eqn-2Dheat_sol2">
    u(x,y,t) = X(x)Y(y)T(t)
  </men>
 
	be  the solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-2Dheat_sol1"/>. 

 
 Then from equation <xref ref="eqn-2Dheat_sol1"/> we have -
 <me>
  YT\frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}}+XT\frac{\partial^{2}Y}{\partial y^{2}} =\frac{XY}{h^{2}}\frac{\partial T}{\partial t}
 </me>
 or,
 <men xml:id="eqn-2Dheat_sol3">
  h^{2}\left[\frac{1}{X}\frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}}+\frac{1}{Y}\frac{\partial^{2}Y}{\partial y^{2}}\right] = \frac{1}{T}\frac{\partial T}{\partial t} = -m \quad (\text{or,}  -\lambda^{2})
 </men>
 
or,
<men xml:id="eqn-2Dheat_sol4">
  \frac{\partial T}{\partial t} =-mT \text{or,}  \frac{\partial T}{\partial t}+mT=0 \Rightarrow T=Ae^{-mt}
</men>

and 
<me>
  \frac{1}{X}\frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}} +\frac{m}{h^{2}}=-\frac{1}{Y}\frac{\partial^{2}Y}{\partial y^{2}}=k^{2}\quad \text{(say)}
</me>
or,
<men xml:id="eqn-2Dheat_sol5">
  \frac{\partial^{2}Y}{\partial y^{2}}+k^{2}Y=0  \quad \Rightarrow Y=B\cos ky+C\sin ky
</men>
also, 
<me>
  \frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}}+\left(\frac{m}{h^{2}}-k^{2}\right)X = 0
</me>

<men xml:id="eqn-2Dheat_sol6">
  \frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}}+p^{2}X = 0 \quad \Rightarrow  X=D\cos px+E\sin px
</men>
where, 
<men xml:id="eqn-2Dheat_sol7">
  p^{2}= \frac{m}{h^{2}}-k^{2}
</men>
    </p>
    		 
Imposing the boundary conditions, we have 
<ol marker="i.">
  <li>
    <p>
      <m> u(x,y,t) = 0</m> at <m>x=0</m> give <m>D=0</m>,
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>u(x,y,t)= 0</m> at <m>y=0</m> gives <m>B=0</m>,     
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
      <m>u(x,y,t)= 0 </m> at <m>x=a</m> i.e., <m>0=Ae^{-mt}[C\sin ky][E\sin pa] </m> 
      <m>\Rightarrow \sin pa =0=\sin r\pi </m>, <m>\therefore  p=\frac{r\pi}{a}</m>, <m>r=1,2,3,\cdots</m>, 
    </p>
  </li>
  <li>
    <p>
     <m>u(x,y,t) = 0</m>  at <m>y=b</m> i.e., <m>0=Ae^{-mt}[C\sin kb][E\sin px]</m>  
     <m>\Rightarrow \sin kb =0=\sin s\pi </m>. <m>\therefore   k=\frac{s\pi}{b}</m>, 
     <m>s=1,2,3,\cdots</m>.
    </p>
  </li>
</ol>
		<p>    
Putting these values in equation <xref ref="eqn-2Dheat_sol7"/>, we get - 
<me>
   \frac{r^{2}\pi^{2}}{a^{2}} =\frac{m}{h^{2}}- \frac{s^{2}\pi^{2}}{b^{2}}
</me>
or,
<me>
  \frac{m}{h^{2}}=\left[\frac{r^{2}}{a^{2}}+ \frac{s^{2}}{b^{2}}\right]\pi^{2}
</me>
<men xml:id="eqn-2Dheat_sol8">
   \therefore   m= h^{2}\pi^{2}\left[\frac{r^{2}}{a^{2}}+ \frac{s^{2}}{b^{2}}\right] = m_{rs}  	\quad (say)
</men>

		
The solution <xref ref="eqn-2Dheat_sol2"/> now becomes -
<me>
  u=\sum\limits_{r=1}^{\infty}\sum\limits_{s=1}^{\infty}A_{rs}e^{-m_{rs}t}\left(E_{r}\sin\frac{r\pi x}{a}\right)\left(C_{s}\sin\frac{s\pi y}{b}\right)
</me>

<men xml:id="eqn-2Dheat_sol9">
  	=\sum\limits_{r,s=1}^{\infty}a_{rs}e^{-m_{rs}t}\sin\frac{r\pi x}{a}\sin\frac{s\pi y}{b}
</men>

To determine the value of constant <m>a_{rs}</m> imposing the initial condition, 
<m>u(x,y,0)=f(x,y)</m>, we get - 
<men xml:id="eqn-2Dheat_sol10">
  f(x,y)=\sum\limits_{r,s=1}^{\infty}a_{rs}\sin\frac{r\pi x}{a}\sin\frac{s\pi y}{b}
</men>
			
multiplying both sides by <m>\sin\frac{r\pi x}{a}\cdot \sin\frac{s\pi y}{b} </m> and 
integrating from 0 to <m>a</m> and <m>b</m>, we get -
<men xml:id="eqn-2Dheat_sol11">
  a_{rs} =\frac{4}{ab}\int\limits_{0}^{a}\int\limits_{0}^{b}	f(x,y)\sin\frac{r\pi x}{a}\cdot \sin\frac{s\pi y}{b}\,dx \,dy			
</men>
  </p>		
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-Lapleqn">
  <title>Laplace's Equation</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      The equation of heat flow in steady state is known as Laplace's equation. i.e., 
      <m>u</m> does not change with time. 
      <me>
         \therefore   \frac{\partial u}{\partial t} =0
      </me>
      and 
      <me>
        \nabla^{2}u = \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial y^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial z^{2}} =0.
      </me>
 
which is a cartesian form of Laplace's equation in three dimensions.
    </p>
    <p>
      In cylindrical coordinates, 
      <me>
        \nabla^{2}u = \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial r^{2}}+\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial \theta^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial z^{2}} =0.
      </me>
      
In spherical polar coordinates, 
<me>
  \nabla^{2}u = \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial r^{2}}+\frac{2}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial \theta^{2}}+\frac{1}{r^{2}\sin\theta}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial \phi^{2}} =0.
</me>
      </p>
  </introduction>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-2D_lapleqn">
    <title>Two Dimensional Laplace's Equation</title>
   <introduction>
    <p>
      The two-dimensional Laplace equation is a partial differential equation that 
      describes the behavior of a scalar function in two dimensions. 
      The general form of the two-dimensional Laplace equation is:
      <me>
        \nabla^{2}u =0
      </me>
where u is the scalar function and <m>\nabla^{2}</m>  is the Laplacian operator. 
In two dimensions, the Laplacian operator can be expressed as the sum of the second 
partial derivatives with respect to the spatial coordinates x and y:
<me>
  \nabla^{2}u = \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2} u}{\partial y^2}
</me>

This equation states that the sum of the second partial derivatives of the function with 
respect to both x and y is equal to zero. The Laplace equation is a special case of the 
more general Poisson equation, where a non-zero source term is present on the right-hand side:
<me>
  \nabla^{2}u =f(x, y)
</me>
    </p>
   </introduction>
   <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-2DLapl_cartsn">
    <title>In Cartesian Coordinates</title>
     <figure xml:id="fig-fig711">
    <caption></caption>
    <image source="fig711.png" width ="45%"/>
</figure>
    <p>
      Consider a thin plate with insulated surfaces bounded by the lines 
      <m>x=0</m>, <m>x=\lambda {,}y=0 </m>, and <m>y=\infty</m>.
Let at steady state, the temp. <m>u(x,y)</m> at any point <m>p(x,y)</m> satisfies the equation 
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn1">
  \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial y^{2}} =0
</men>
	
assuming the edges <m>x=0</m> and  <m>x=\lambda </m> is kept at temperature zero and also 
the lower edge <m>y=0</m> is kept at tempemperature <m>f(x)</m> and the edge <m>y=\infty</m> at zero temperature.
      </p>
      <p>
        Then solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn1"/> is given by	
        <men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn2">
          u(x,y) = X(x)Y(y)
        </men>

Now three possible solutions of equation <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn1"/> are 
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn3">
  u=\left(C_{1}e^{px}+C_{2}e^{-px}\right)\left(C_{3}\cos py+C_{4}\sin py\right)
</men>
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn4">
  u=\left(C_{5}\cos px+C_{6}\sin px\right)\left(C_{7}e^{py}+C_{8}e^{-py}\right)
</men>
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn5">
  u=\left(C_{9}x+C_{10}\right)\left(C_{11}y+C_{12}\right)
</men>

Of these, we have to choose that solution which is consistant with the physical nature 
of the problem. The solution <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn3"/> and <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn5"/> 
can not satisfy the boundary conditions. Therefore,  possible solution is only 
<xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn4"/>. From the boundary condition, <m>u(0,y) =0</m>, 
we have from solution <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn4"/>, 
<me>
  0= C_{5}\left(C_{7}e^{py}+C_{8}e^{-py}\right)\Rightarrow C_{5} =0.
</me>

therefore, solution <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn4"/> reduces to 
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn6">
  u=C_{6}\sin px\left(C_{7}e^{py}+C_{8}e^{-py}\right)		
</men>

using  <m>u(\lambda,y) =0</m>, we have - 
<me>
   0= C_{6}\sin p\lambda\left(C_{7}e^{py}+C_{8}e^{-py}\right)\quad \because  C_{6} \neq 0,
</me>
and 
<me>
  \sin p\lambda = 0=\sin n\pi   \quad  \therefore  p=\frac{n\pi}{\lambda},  \quad n=1,2,3,\cdots	
</me>
	
also to satisfy the condition <m>u(x,\infty)=0, \quad  C_{7} =0</m>. 
Hence equation <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn6"/> takes the form 
<m>u(x,y) = C_{6}C_{8}\sin px \cdot e^{-py}</m>. Or,
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn7">
  u(x,y) = \sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty}b_{n}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}\cdot e^{-\frac{n\pi y}{\lambda}}
</men>

But the initial condition <m>u(x,0) =f(x)</m>, we have 
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn8">
  f(x)=\sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty}b_{n}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}
</men>
where 
<me>
  b_{n} = \frac{2}{\lambda}\int\limits_{0}^{\lambda}f(x)\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}\,dx
</me>

If the given plate is of finite length <m>a</m> and the temp. at this end is 
<m>u=f(x) </m>, then the boundary conditions are  <m>u(0,y) =0=u(\lambda,y)=u(x,0)</m> 
and <m>u(x,a)=f(x) </m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          Let the solution of this problem is 
          <men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn9">
            	u=\left(C_{1}\cos px+C_{2}\sin px\right)\left(C_{3}e^{py}+C_{4}e^{-py}\right)
          </men>
          putting <m>x=0</m> and <m>u=0</m> in eqn. <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn9"/>, we have
<me>
  0=C_{1}\left(C_{3}e^{py}+C_{4}e^{-py}\right) \quad \Rightarrow  C_{1} =0 
</me>
hence eqn. <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn9"/> reduces to 
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn10">
  u=C_{2}\sin px\left(C_{3}e^{py}+C_{4}e^{-py}\right)	
</men>

on putting <m>x=\lambda</m> and <m>u=0</m>, we have -
<me>
  0=C_{2}\sin p\lambda\left(C_{3}e^{py}+C_{4}e^{-py}\right)
</me>
or,
<me>
  \sin p\lambda =0=\sin n\pi	\quad \text{as}\quad  C_{2} \neq 0 
</me>
or,
<me>
  p=\frac{n\pi}{\lambda},	\quad n=1,2,3,\cdots 
</me>

Now equation <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn10"/> becomes -
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn11">
  u=C_{2}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}\left(C_{3}e^{\frac{n\pi y}{\lambda}}+C_{4}e^{-\frac{n\pi y}{\lambda}}\right)
</men>
		
on putting <m>u=0</m> and <m>y=0</m> in equation <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn11"/>, we get - 
<me>
  0= C_{2}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}(C_{3}+C_{4}) \quad  \Rightarrow  C_{3}+C_{4} =0 
</me>
or, <m>C_{4} =-C_{3}</m>
	
therefore, equation <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn11"/> becomes 
<me>
  u=C_{2}C_{3}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}\left(e^{\frac{n\pi y}{\lambda}}-e^{-\frac{n\pi y}{\lambda}}\right)
</me>
or,
<me>
  u=\sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty}b_{n}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}\left(e^{\frac{n\pi y}{\lambda}}-e^{-\frac{n\pi y}{\lambda}}\right)\times\frac{2}{2}
</me>
or,
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn12">
  u=\sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty}c_{n}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}\sin\frac{n\pi y}{\lambda}  
</men>
<m>[\because  \quad 2b_{n} =c_{n}]</m>.

on putting <m>y=a</m> and <m>u=f(x)</m> in equation <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn12"/>, we get -
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_cartsn13">
  f(x) =\sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty}c_{n}\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}\sin\frac{n\pi y}{\lambda}
</men>
where 
<me>
   c_{n}\sinh \frac{n\pi a}{\lambda} = \frac{2}{\lambda}\int\limits_{0}^{\lambda}f(x)\sin\frac{n\pi x}{\lambda}\,dx.
</me>

          </p>
   </subsubsection>

  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-2DLapl_ccylnd">
    <title>In Cylindrical Coordinates</title>
    <p>
      The Laplace equation in two dimensional case is 
      <men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd1">
        	\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial r^{2}}+\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial \theta^{2}}=0	
      </men>
      Let 
      <men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd2">
        u(r,\theta) = R(r)\Theta(\theta) 
      </men>
      	be the solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd1"/>, so that	
        <men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd3">
          \Theta\frac{\partial^{2}R}{\partial r^{2}}+\frac{\Theta}{r}\frac{\partial R}{\partial r}+\frac{R}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial^{2}\Theta}{\partial \theta^{2}}
        </men>
        or,
        <men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd4">
           \frac{1}{R}\left(r^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}R}{\partial r^{2}}+r\frac{\partial R}{\partial r}\right) =-\frac{1}{\Theta}\frac{\partial^{2}\Theta}{\partial \theta^{2}}=n^{2} \quad	\text{(say)}	
        </men>
        <men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd5">
          r^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}R}{\partial r^{2}}+r\frac{\partial R}{\partial r}=-n^{2}R=0	
        </men>
      </p>
      <p>
        This is a homogenous linear differential equation. Its solution can be found by 
        putting <m>r=e^{z}</m> or, <m>\log r=z</m> or, 
        
        <me>
          \frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial r}{\partial z} =1.
        </me>
        or,

      <men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd6">
        \frac{\partial r}{\partial z} =r
      </men>
      Also,
      <me>
         \frac{\partial R}{\partial r} =\frac{\partial R}{\partial z}\cdot\frac{\partial z}{\partial r} = \frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial R}{\partial z}
      </me>
    or,  
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd7">
   r\frac{\partial R}{\partial r}=\frac{\partial R}{\partial z}= DR   
</men>
assume 
<me>
  D\equiv \frac{\partial }{\partial z}.
</me>
 
again, 
<me>
  \frac{\partial^{2}R}{\partial r^{2}} = \frac{\partial }{\partial r}\left(\frac{\partial R}{\partial r}\right)  = \frac{\partial }{\partial z}\left(\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial R}{\partial z}\right)\frac{\partial z}{\partial z}	
</me>

<me>
  	= \frac{1}{r}\left[\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial^{2}R}{\partial z^{2}}- \frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial r}{\partial z}\frac{\partial R}{\partial z}\right]  = \frac{1}{r}\left[\frac{1}{r}D^{2}R- \frac{1}{r^{2}}\cdot r\cdot DR\right]
</me>

  or,
  <me>
    r^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}R}{\partial r^{2}}=D^{2}R-DR=D(D-1)R 
  </me>
  
from eqn.<xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd5"/>,
<me>
   D(D-1)R+DR-n^{2}R =0
</me>
or,
<me>
  D^{2}R -DR+DR-n^{2}R =0
</me>
or,
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd8">
  (D^{2}-n^{2})R=0
</men>

or,
<me>
  D=\pm n
</me>
or,
<me>
  R=C_{1}e^{nz} +C_{2}e^{-nz}
</me>
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd9">
 \therefore  R=C_{1}r^{n}+C_{2}r^{-n} 
</men>

<me>
  [e^{nz}=e^{n\log r}=e^{\log r^{n}} = r^{n}].
</me>
and 
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd10">
  \frac{\partial^{2}\Theta}{\partial \theta^{2}}+n^{2}\Theta =0 \quad  \Rightarrow  \Theta =C_{3}\cos n\theta + C_{4}\sin n\theta 
</men>

 Hence, 
 <men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd11">
  u_{n}=\left(C_{1}r^{n}+C_{2}r^{-n}\right)\left(C_{3}\cos n\theta+C_{4}\sin n\theta\right)
 </men>
        </p>
        <p>
          If <m>n=0</m>, we have from equation <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd10"/>, 
          <men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd12">
            \frac{\partial^{2}\Theta}{\partial \theta^{2}} =0 \quad \Rightarrow  \Theta = A_{o}\theta+B_{o}
          </men>
          

from equation <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd8"/>, we get -	
<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd13">
  D^{2}R =0  \quad  \Rightarrow  R = C_{o}z+D_{o} =  C_{o}\log r + D_{o}
</men>
	Hence, 
  <men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd14">
     u_{o}=(A_{o}\theta+B_{o})(C_{o}\log r + D_{o})
  </men>
  		
				
But the general single - valued solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd1"/> 
for all possible value of <m>n</m> may be written as 
<me>
    u=a_{o}\log r+\sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty}r^{n}(a_{n}\cos n\theta +b_{n}\cos n\theta)
</me>

<men xml:id="eqn-2DLapl_ccylnd15">
+\sum\limits_{n=1}^{\infty}r^{-n}(p_{n}\cos n\theta +q_{n}\cos n\theta)+c_{o}
</men>
          </p>
  </subsubsection>
  </subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-3D_heat">
  <title>Three Dimensional Equation of Heat Flow</title>
  <p>
    Three dimensional heat equation is given by 
    <men xml:id="eqn-3D_heat1">
      \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial y^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial z^{2}} =\frac{1}{h^{2}}\frac{\partial u}{\partial t}
    </men>
 
the solution of which is assumed as      
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_heat2">
  u=u(x,y,z,t)=X(x)Y(y)Z(z)T(t)
</men>

By substitution of this in equation <xref ref="eqn-3D_heat1"/>, we get -
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_heat3">
  \frac{1}{X}\frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}}+\frac{1}{Y}\frac{\partial^{2}Y}{\partial y^{2}}+\frac{1}{Z}\frac{\partial^{2}Z}{\partial z^{2}} =\frac{1}{h^{2}T}\frac{\partial T}{\partial t} =-\lambda^{2}   \text{(say)}
</men>
Now
<me>
\frac{1}{X}\frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}} =-\lambda_{1}^{2}; 
</me>
or,
<me>
  \frac{1}{Y}\frac{\partial^{2}Y}{\partial y^{2}} = -\lambda_{2}^{2}; 
</me>
or,
<me>
  \frac{1}{Z}\frac{\partial^{2}Z}{\partial z^{2}} =-\lambda_{3}^{2}, 
</me>
so that 
<me>
  \lambda^{2} = \lambda_{1}^{2}+\lambda_{2}^{2}+\lambda_{3}^{2}
</me>
Yielding 
<me>
  X=A\cos\lambda_{1}x+B\sin\lambda_{1}x = a\cos(\lambda_{1}x+\alpha\lambda_{1});
</me>
or,
<me>
  Y=b\cos(\lambda_{2}y+\alpha\lambda_{2}),
</me>
or,
<me>
   Z =c\cos(\lambda_{3}z+\alpha\lambda_{3}),
</me>
and 
<me>
  T=de^{-\lambda^{2}h^{2}t}=de^{-(\lambda_{1}^{2}+\lambda_{2}^{2}+\lambda_{3}^{2})h^{2}t}
</me>
    	
Hence for all values of <m>t</m>,  the general solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-3D_heat1"/> is
   <me>
   u=\sum\limits_{\lambda_{1}=0}^{\infty}\sum\limits_{\lambda_{2}=0}^{\infty}\sum\limits_{\lambda_{3}=0}^{\infty}A_{\lambda_{1}\lambda_{2}\lambda_{3}}\cos(\lambda_{1}x+\alpha\lambda_{1})\cos(\lambda_{2}y+\alpha\lambda_{2}) 
   </me>
   <me>
    \cos(\lambda_{3}z+\alpha\lambda_{3})e^{-h^{2}(\lambda_{1}^{2}+\lambda_{2}^{2}+\lambda_{3}^{2})t} 
   </me>   
    </p>
</subsection>

<subsection xml:id="subsec-3D_lapleq">
  <title>Three Dimensional Laplace's Equation</title>
  <introduction>
    <p>
      The Laplace equation arises in various physical problems, including electrostatics, 
      heat conduction, fluid flow, and potential theory. Solving the 3D Laplace equation 
      involves finding a function <m>u(x)</m> that satisfies the equation <m>\nabla^{2}u =0</m>. 
      This typically involves specifying appropriate boundary conditions or constraints 
      on the function at the boundaries of the domain. The solutions to the Laplace equation
       are harmonic functions, which have many interesting mathematical properties.
    </p>
  </introduction>
  <subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-3D_laplRect">
    <title>In Rectangular Coordinates</title>
    <p> <idx>rectangular coordinates</idx>
      The equation is 		
      <men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplRect1">
        \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial x^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial y^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial z^{2}} =0
      </men>
      Let 
      <men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplRect2">
        u=X(x)Y(y)Z(z) 
      </men>
      be the solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-3D_laplRect1"/>
Then 
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplRect3">
  \frac{1}{X}\frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}}+\frac{1}{Y}\frac{\partial^{2}Y}{\partial y^{2}}+\frac{1}{Z}\frac{\partial^{2}Z}{\partial z^{2}} =0
</men>

In equation <xref ref="eqn-3D_laplRect3"/> all are independent to each other 
hence each may be seperately equal to some constant, i.e., 
<me>
  \frac{1}{X}\frac{\partial^{2}X}{\partial x^{2}} =n^{2} \quad  \Rightarrow X=A\cos nx+B\sin nx,
</me>
or,
<me>
  \frac{1}{Y}\frac{\partial^{2}Y}{\partial y^{2}} =-m^{2} \quad  \Rightarrow Y=C\cos my+D\sin my,
</me>
and 
<me>
  \frac{1}{Z}\frac{\partial^{2}Z}{\partial z^{2}}=p^{2} \quad  \Rightarrow Z=Ee^{pz}+Fe^{-pz}
</me>
Thus, the general solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-3D_laplRect1"/> is 
<me>
  u=(A\cos nx+B\sin nx)
</me>

<men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplRect4">
  (C\cos my+D\sin my)(Ee^{pz}+Fe^{-pz})
</men>
	where <m>p^{2}=m^{2}+n^{2}</m>.					
      </p>
      <p>
        Alternative solution of equation <xref ref="eqn-3D_laplRect1"/> is 
        <me>
           u=(Ae^{nx}+Be^{-nx})
        </me>
        
 <men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplRect5">
  (Ce^{my}+De^{-my})(E\cos{pz}+F\sin{pz})
 </men>
        </p>
  </subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-3D_laplcyl">
  <title>In Cylindrical Coordinates</title>
  <p>
    <idx>cylindrical coordinates</idx>
    We have,
    <men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplcyl1">
      \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial r^{2}}+\frac{1}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial \theta^{2}}+\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial z^{2}} =0
    </men>
    Let 
    <men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplcyl2">
      u(r,\theta,z) =R(r)\Theta(\theta)Z(z) 
    </men>
    be the solution of eqn.<xref ref="eqn-3D_laplcyl1"/>. Hence,
    <men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplcyl3">
      \frac{1}{R}\frac{\partial^{2}R}{\partial r^{2}}+\frac{1}{rR}\frac{\partial R}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{r^{2}\Theta}\frac{\partial^{2}\Theta}{\partial \theta^{2}}+\frac{1}{Z}\frac{\partial^{2}Z}{\partial z^{2}} =0
    </men>

As variables are separated, we may take - 
<me>
  \frac{1}{Z}\frac{\partial^{2}Z}{\partial z^{2}}=\lambda^{2}
</me>
or,
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplcyl4">
  \frac{\partial^{2}Z}{\partial z^{2}}-\lambda^{2}Z =0 \quad \Rightarrow Z=Ae^{\lambda z}+Be^{-\lambda z}
</men>
and 
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplcyl5">
  \frac{r^{2}}{R}\frac{\partial^{2}R}{\partial r^{2}}+\frac{r}{R}\frac{\partial R}{\partial r}+\lambda^{2}r^{2}=-\frac{1}{\Theta}\frac{\partial^{2}\Theta}{\partial \theta^{2}}=\mu^{2}
</men>

also, 
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplcyl6">
  \frac{1}{\Theta}\frac{\partial^{2}\Theta}{\partial \theta^{2}}+\mu^{2}\Theta =0 \quad \Rightarrow \Theta = C\cos \mu \theta +D\sin \mu\theta
</men>
and 
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplcyl7">
  r^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}R}{\partial r^{2}}+r\frac{\partial R}{\partial r}+(\lambda^{2}r^{2}-\mu^{2})R=0
</men>

Now put <m>\lambda  r=s </m> so that 
<me>
  \frac{\partial }{\partial r} = \frac{\partial }{\partial s}\cdot \frac{\partial s}{\partial r}=+\lambda \frac{\partial }{\partial s}
</me>
and 
<me>
  \frac{\partial^{2} }{\partial r^{2}} =\lambda^{2} \frac{\partial^{2} }{\partial s^{2}}
</me>

therefore equation <xref ref="eqn-3D_laplcyl7"/> reduces to
<me>
  \frac{s^{2}}{\lambda^{2}}\lambda^{2}\frac{\partial^{2} R}{\partial s^{2}}+\frac{s}{\lambda}\lambda \frac{\partial R}{\partial s}+(s^{2}-\mu^{2})R =0
</me>
or,
<me>
  s^{2}\frac{\partial^{2} R}{\partial s^{2}}+s\frac{\partial R}{\partial s}+(s^{2}-\mu^{2})R =0 
</me>

which is Bessel's equation and it's general solution is given as  
<me>
  R=EJ_{\mu}(s)+FJ_{-\mu}(s)
</me>
or,
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplcyl8">
  R=EJ_{\mu}(\lambda r)+FJ_{-\mu}(\lambda r)
</men>


since <m>u(r,\theta,z)</m> be finite at <m>r \to 0 </m>, we have  
<me>
  s=\lambda r =0 \Rightarrow  J_{-\mu} \to \infty
</me>
or,
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_laplcyl9">
  \therefore  R= EJ_{\mu}(\lambda r)
</men>
Hence, 
<me>
  u(r,\theta,z)  = (Ae^{\lambda z}+Be^{-\lambda z})(C\cos \mu \theta +D\sin \mu\theta)[EJ_{\mu}(\lambda r)]
</me>			
    </p>
</subsubsection>

<subsubsection xml:id="subsubsec-3D_lalpsph">
  <title>In Spherical Coordinates</title>
  <p>
    <me>
       \frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial r^{2}}
    </me>
    
    <men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph1">
     +\frac{2}{r}\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial \theta^{2}}+\frac{\cot\theta}{r^{2}}\frac{\partial u}{\partial \theta}+\frac{1}{r^{2}\sin ^{2}\theta}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial \phi^{2}} =0
    </men>
    or,
    <me>
       r^{2}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial r^{2}}
    </me>
    
    <men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph2">
     +2r\frac{\partial u}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{\sin\theta}\frac{\partial }{\partial \theta}\left(\sin\theta\frac{\partial u}{\partial \theta}\right)+\frac{1}{\sin ^{2}\theta}\frac{\partial^{2}u}{\partial \phi^{2}} =0
    </men>
    Suppose, 
    <men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph3">
     u(r,\theta,\phi) = R(r)\Theta(\theta)\Phi(\phi)
    </men>
    be its solution.
    Then, 
    <me>
       \left[\frac{r^{2}}{R}\frac{\partial^{2}R}{\partial r^{2}}+\frac{2r}{R}\frac{\partial R}{\partial r}+\frac{1}{\Theta\sin\theta}\frac{\partial }{\partial \theta}\left(\sin\theta\frac{\partial \Theta}{\partial \theta}\right)\right]\sin ^{2}\theta 
    </me>
 <men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph4">
  = -\frac{1}{\Phi}\frac{\partial^{2}\Phi}{\partial \phi^{2}} = \lambda^{2}  \quad  \text{(say)}
 </men>

 considering eqn.<xref ref="eqn-3D_lalpsph4"/>,
 <men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph5">
  \frac{1}{\Phi}\frac{\partial^{2}\Phi}{\partial \phi^{2}} = -\lambda^{2} \quad \Rightarrow \Phi=Ce^{\pm i\lambda \phi}
 </men>
 and 
 <me>
   \frac{1}{R}\frac{\partial }{\partial r}\left(r^{2}\frac{\partial R}{\partial r}\right) 
 </me>
 
 <men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph6">
  -\frac{1}{\Theta\sin\theta}\frac{\partial }{\partial \theta}\left(\sin\theta\frac{\partial \Theta}{\partial \theta}\right)+\frac{\lambda^{2}}{\sin^{2}\theta} =n(n+1) \quad \text{(say)}
 </men>
 or,
 <men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph7">
  \frac{\partial }{\partial r}\left(r^{2}\frac{\partial R}{\partial r}\right)-n(n+1)R =0
 </men>
 and 
 <men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph8">
  \frac{1}{\sin\theta}\frac{\partial }{\partial \theta}\left(\sin\theta\frac{\partial \Theta}{\partial \theta}\right)+\left[n(n+1)-\frac{\lambda^{2}}{\sin^{2}\theta}\right]\Theta =0
 </men>	

As equation <xref ref="eqn-3D_lalpsph7"/> being the homogenous, put <m>r=e^{z} </m>, 
hence equation <xref ref="eqn-3D_lalpsph7"/> reduces to 
<me>
  [D(D-1)+2D-n(n+1)]R=0  
</me>
where, <m>D\equiv \frac{\partial }{\partial z}</m>.
or, 
<me>
  [D^{2}+D-n(n+1)]R =0
</me>
or,
<me>
  (D-n)(D+n+1)R =0
</me>

or,
<me>
   D=n,-(n+1),
</me>
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph9">
  \therefore R=Ae^{nz}+Be^{-(n+1)z} = Ar^{n}+Br^{-n-1}
</men>

			 	
again, if we put <m>\cos\theta =\mu </m> in equation <xref ref="eqn-3D_lalpsph8"/>, then since 
<me>
   \frac{\partial \Theta}{\partial\theta} = \frac{\partial \Theta}{\partial\mu} \cdot \frac{\partial \mu}{\partial\theta} =-\sin\theta \frac{\partial \Theta}{\partial\mu}
</me>
or, 
<me>
 \frac{1}{\sin\theta} \frac{\partial }{\partial\theta}=-\frac{\partial }{\partial\mu}  
</me>


 we have,
 <me>
   \frac{\partial }{\partial\mu} \left\{(1-\mu^{2})\frac{\partial \Theta}{\partial\mu} \right\}+\left\{n(n+1)-\frac{\lambda^{2}}{1-\mu^{2}}\right\}\Theta =0 
 </me>
 Now,
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph10">
  (1-\mu^{2})\frac{\partial^{2} \Theta}{\partial\mu^{2}}-2\mu \frac{\partial \Theta}{\partial\mu}+\left\{n(n+1)--\frac{\lambda^{2}}{1-\mu^{2}}\right\}\Theta =0
</men>


which is Legendre's associated differential equational and hence has the solution,
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph11">
  \Theta =AP^{\lambda}_{n}(\mu)+BQ^{\lambda}_{n}(\mu)=AP^{\lambda}_{n}(\cos\theta)+BQ^{\lambda}_{n}(\cos\theta)
</men>
   		
Now as <m>\Theta</m> is the function of <m>\cos\theta </m>, then solution of equation 
<xref ref="eqn-3D_lalpsph1"/> is in the form 
<me>
  u=(Ar^{n}+Br^{-n-1})\Theta(\cos\theta)e^{\pm i\lambda\phi}
</me>

The summing over all <m>n</m>, the general solution of equation 
<xref ref="eqn-3D_lalpsph1"/> may be written as 
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph12">
  u(r,\theta,\phi) = \sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}(Ar^{n}+Br^{-n-1})\Theta(\cos\theta)e^{\pm i\lambda\phi}
</men>
 </p>

<p>
  <term>Note 1.</term>
If <m>\lambda=0</m>, then equation <xref ref="eqn-3D_lalpsph10"/> reduces to Legendre's equation, 
<me>
  \Theta = P_{n}(\mu)=P_{n}(\cos\theta)
</me>
also, 
<me>
  \Theta = Q_{n}(\mu)=Q_{n}(\cos\theta).
</me>
Thus, 
<me>
  \Theta = C_{n}P_{n}(\mu)+D_{n}Q_{n}(\mu) 
</me>

so that	
<me>
    u(r,\theta,\phi) = \sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}\left(A_{n}r^{n}+\frac{B_{n}}{r^{n+1}}\right)\{C_{n}P_{n}(\cos\theta) 
</me>
 
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph13">
+D_{n}Q_{n}(\cos\theta)\} e^{\pm i\lambda\phi}
</men>


In case <m>D_{n}=0</m> under specific boundary conditions, 
then <m>\Theta =  C_{n}P_{n}(\cos\theta)</m> 


<men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph14">
   \therefore u= \sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}\left(A_{n}r^{n} +\frac{B_{n}}{r^{n+1}}\right)C_{n}P_{n}(\cos\theta) e^{\pm i\lambda\phi}
</men>
</p>

		<p>
   <term>Note 2.</term>   If there is axial symmetry about z - axis, then <m>u</m> 
   depens only upon <m>r</m> and <m>\theta</m> so that <m>\phi =0 </m> in equation 
   <xref ref="eqn-3D_lalpsph14"/>, 
<men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph15">
  u(r,\theta) = \sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}\left(A_{n}r^{n}+\frac{B_{n}}{r^{n+1}}\right)\{C_{n}P_{n}(\cos\theta)+D_{n}Q_{n}(\cos\theta)\}
</men>

 If <m> D_{n}=0</m>,	
 <men xml:id="eqn-3D_lalpsph16">
   u(r,\theta) = \sum\limits_{n=0}^{\infty}\left(A_{n}r^{n}+\frac{B_{n}}{r^{n+1}}\right)C_{n}P_{n}(\cos\theta)
 </men>
      </p> 
</subsubsection>
</subsection>
  </section>

